A large-scale epidemic linked to food in China could have serious repercussions, impacting events like the 2008 Beijing Olympics.
Tainted foodstuffs also threaten China's food export industry.
The Asian Development Bank warns that tainted food affects 300 million Chinese annually, leading to potential disease outbreaks.
Efforts to improve food safety include city evaluations and emergency plans.
Calls for a unified food safety mechanism and stricter punishments for violations have been made.
With concerns rising, a lawmaker suggests a trans-ministry agency for better supervision.
The Health Ministry aims to strengthen coordination and accountability in food safety inspections nationwide.
